ENTRY            D6075   20260414   20260528   20260528       D152
SUBENT        D6075001   20260414   20260528   20260528       D152
BIB                 14         57
TITLE      Determination of the 233Pa(n,f) reaction cross
            section from 11.5 to 16.5 MeV neutron energy by the
            hybrid surrogate ratio approach
AUTHOR     (B.K.Nayak, A.Saxena, D.C.Biswas, E.T.Mirgule,
           B.V.John, S.Santra, R.P.Vind, R.K.Choudhury,
           S.Ganesan)
INSTITUTE  (3INDTRM)
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,78,061602,2008)
FACILITY   (VDGT,3INDTAT)
SAMPLE     A self-supporting thorium target of thickness
            2.0 mg/cm2 was bombarded with a 6Li beam.
DETECTOR   (SOLST,SISD) a solid state delta E - E telescope of
            thickness 150.0 micro millimeter to 1.0 millimeter was
            kept at 90 degree with respect to the beam direction
            around the transfer grazing angle to identify the
            projectile-like-fragments (PLF). A 16 strip solid
            state detector (each strip of size 2.0 X 64.0 mm) was
            placed at a back angle covering the laboratory angular
            range of 141-158 degree to detect fission fragments in
            coincidence with PLFs.
METHOD     (EDE) The proton, deuteron, triton, alpha and 6-Li
            particles are uniquely identified by plotting delta
            E against the delta E + E. This plot was transformed
            to create an effective particle identification versus
            energy plot.
INC-SOURCE A self-supporting thorium was bombarded with 6-Li
           beam of energy 38.0 MeV from a 14 MV Pelletron
           accelerator at Mumbai.
ANALYSIS   (SURGT) The 234-Pa and 236-U compound systems have
           been populated at overlapping excitation energies in
           the same experiment through 232-Th (6-Li,A) 234-Pa and
           232-Th (6-Li,D) 236-U transfer channels at E (lab) = 38
           MeV, and the absolute surrogate method is used to
           determine fission decay probabilities of the above
           compound nuclei by dividing the number of PLF-fission
           coincidences by the associated PLF-singles data. The
           experimental values of fission decay probability
           ratios of 234-Pa and 236-U compound nuclei at the same
           excitation energies have been used to deduce the 233-Pa
            (n,f) cross-section using a surrogate ratio approach.
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-S) The uncertainties shown in the measured cross
           section is due to the statistics of coincidence
           counts in each energy beam.
COMMENT    A hybrid surrogate ratio approach was used to determine
            neutron-induced fission cross sections of 233Pa in
            the 11.5-16.5 MeV range. The cross sections were
            obtained from fission decay probability ratios of
            234Pa and 236U using the surrogate ratio method.
           The results, with data from 1.0-16.5 MeV, were compared
            with EMPIRE-2.19. The present data agree with the
            model, but earlier data differ in 7.0-10.0 MeV range.
STATUS     (APRVD) Entry approved by B.K.Nayak
HISTORY    (20090803C) Mr.Paresh Prajapati, M.S. University of
            Baroda and Dr.S.Ganesan of Reactor Physics Design
            Division, B.A.R.C, Mumbai.
           (20260414U) VT. Entry revised. COMMENT: open
